7s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Median and ulnar","Musculocutaneous and axillary","Radial and axillary","Musculocutaneous and radial","Ulnar and radial"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is the \u003Cstrong\u003Emusculocutaneous \u003C/strong\u003E(C5-C7)\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial \u003C/strong\u003E(C5-T1) nerves. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emusculocutaneous nerve \u003C/strong\u003Einnervates the anterior compartment of the arm, allowing for \u003Cstrong\u003Eelbow flexion\u003C/strong\u003E and supination. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the posterior compartments of the arm and forearm, allowing for elbow extension, \u003Cstrong\u003Ewrist extension\u003C/strong\u003E, finger extension and supination. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian nerve \u003C/strong\u003E(C6-T1) innervates the entire anterior compartment of the forearm (except flexor carpi ulnaris and medial part of flexor digitorium profundus). This provides flexion of the wrist, finger flexion and pronation. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar nerve \u003C/strong\u003E(C8-T1) innervates two muscles of the anterior compartment of the forearm (Flexor carpi ulnaris and medial part of flexor digitorium) and intrinsic muscles the hand. Allowing for wrist flexion, wrist adduction, flexion (metacarpophalangeal joint) and extension (interphalangeal joint) of the 4th and 5th digits and finger adduction, abduction and opposition. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve \u003C/strong\u003E(C5-C6) innervates the deltoid and teres minor allowing for shoulder abduction (15-90 degrees), shoulder flexion, extension and external rotation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The musculocutaneous nerve innervates the anterior compartment of the arm allowing 